    "body" : "<p>You need to <a href=\"http://www.janeg.ca/scjp/lang/arrays.html\" rel=\"noreferrer\">initialize</a> <code>errorSoon</code>, as indicated by the error message, you have only <a href=\"http://java.sun.com/docs/books/tutorial/java/nutsandbolts/arrays.html\" rel=\"noreferrer\">declared</a> it.</p>\n\n<pre><code>String[] errorSoon;                   // &lt;--declared statement\nString[] errorSoon = new String[100]; // &lt;--initialized statement\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>You need to initialize the array so it can allocate the correct memory storage for the <code>String</code> elements <em>before</em> you can start setting the index.</p>\n\n<p>If you <em>only</em> declare the array (as you did) there is no memory allocated for the <code>String</code> elements, but only a reference handle to <code>errorSoon</code>, and will throw an error when you try to initialize a variable at any index.</p>\n\n<p>As a side note, you could also initialize the <code>String</code> array inside braces, <code>{ }</code> as so,</p>\n\n<pre><code>String[] errorSoon = {\"Hello\", \"World\"};\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>which is equivalent to</p>\n\n<pre><code>String[] errorSoon = new String[2];\nerrorSoon[0] = \"Hello\";\nerrorSoon[1] = \"World\";\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 115700,
      "reputation" : 1577,
      "user_id" : 303674,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/024f298f0da1bb8dc67bf5dfc549b7db?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
